<h2>HVAC Systems in Florida</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Florida's subtropical and tropical climate zones create unique challenges and requirements for HVAC systems that must operate efficiently in high heat and humidity conditions for extended periods. The state experiences average summer temperatures ranging from 85-90¬∞F, with humidity levels frequently exceeding 70%, creating heat index values that often surpass 100¬∞F. This combination of heat and moisture requires HVAC systems that excel not only at temperature control but also at dehumidification to maintain indoor comfort and air quality.</p>

<p>The cooling season in Florida typically extends from April through October, with many regions requiring air conditioning operation for 8-9 months annually. During peak summer months, HVAC systems may operate 12-16 hours per day, making energy efficiency critical for managing utility costs. Average annual cooling degree days range from 3,000 in northern Florida to over 4,500 in southern regions, significantly higher than most other states. This extended cooling demand means that HVAC efficiency directly impacts both comfort and energy expenses throughout most of the year.</p>

<p>Florida's climate also presents challenges related to salt air corrosion in coastal areas, frequent thunderstorms, and occasional extreme weather events. HVAC equipment must be selected and installed to withstand these environmental factors while maintaining reliable operation. Additionally, the state's high humidity levels require careful attention to indoor air quality, mold prevention, and proper ventilation to ensure healthy living environments.</p>

